# 🛰️ Automated Sentinel-2 Image Classification Pipeline

> Teaching a computer to look at satellite photos of the Earth and say what's on the ground — forests, rivers, farms, cities, and more.

This project takes **real satellite images** of any place on Earth and automatically labels what each part of the image is (forest, water, crop land, residential area, etc.) using deep learning.

---

## 🌍 What does this project do? (in simple terms)

Imagine you point at a spot on the map and ask: *"What's down there?"*

This pipeline answers that automatically:

1. **You pick a location** (a box on the map) and a **date range**.
2. The program **downloads a real satellite photo** of that area from Microsoft's free satellite database.
3. It **cuts the big photo into small square tiles**.
4. A trained AI model **looks at each tile** and says what it is — forest, river, farmland, city, etc.
5. It **shows you the results** as a labeled grid of images.

No manual downloading, no manual labeling — the whole thing runs end to end.

---

## 🧠 The AI behind it

I trained two different models on a well-known satellite image dataset (**EuroSAT**) and compared them:

| Model | What it is | How accurate? |
|-------|-----------|---------------|
| 🥇 **ResNet** (custom) | A deeper network that uses "skip connections" to learn better | **93.15%** ✅ |
| 🥈 **CNN** (baseline) | A simpler network, used for comparison | 80.72% |

**Takeaway:** The ResNet was about **12% more accurate** than the simple CNN — which shows why modern "residual" networks work so well for image tasks.

---

## 📸 What can it recognize?

The model sorts each piece of land into one of **10 categories:**

🌾 Annual Crop &nbsp;&nbsp; 🌲 Forest &nbsp;&nbsp; 🌿 Herbaceous Vegetation &nbsp;&nbsp; 🛣️ Highway &nbsp;&nbsp; 🏭 Industrial
🐄 Pasture &nbsp;&nbsp; 🌳 Permanent Crop &nbsp;&nbsp; 🏘️ Residential &nbsp;&nbsp; 🏞️ River &nbsp;&nbsp; 🌊 Sea / Lake

---

## 📊 The dataset

I used **EuroSAT** — a popular collection of satellite image tiles taken from the Sentinel-2 satellite.

- **21,600** images for training (teaching the model)
- **5,400** images for testing (checking how well it learned)
- Every image resized to **64×64 pixels**

---

## 📁 What's in this repository?

```
.
├── sentinel2_classification_pipeline.ipynb   <- The main program (downloads + classifies live images)
├── ResNet_model_training.ipynb               <- How I trained the ResNet (93.15% accurate)
├── CNN_model_training.ipynb                  <- How I trained the simpler CNN (80.72% accurate)
├── ResNet_model/                             <- Saved ResNet model files
└── CNN_model/                                <- Saved CNN model files
```

> 💡 **New here? Start with `sentinel2_classification_pipeline.ipynb`** — that's the main demo that ties everything together.

---

## 🛠️ Tools & libraries used

- **PyTorch** — to build and train the AI models
- **Planetary Computer + pystac-client + stackstac** — to download real satellite images
- **NumPy, Pillow, Matplotlib, seaborn** — to handle and display images
- **scikit-learn** — to measure accuracy

---

## ▶️ How to run it yourself

**1. Install the required libraries:**

```bash
pip install torch torchvision numpy scikit-image pillow matplotlib seaborn scikit-learn \
            pystac-client planetary-computer stackstac dask tqdm
```

**2. Open the main notebook** `sentinel2_classification_pipeline.ipynb` and set where and when you want to look:

```python
BBOX       = [77.5, 12.8, 78.0, 13.2]    # the map area: [left, bottom, right, top]
TIME_RANGE = "2022-01-01/2022-01-31"      # the date range to search for photos
MODEL_PATH = "ResNet_model/ResNet_classification_Model.pth"   # the trained model
```

**3. Run all the cells.** The notebook will fetch a satellite image, slice it up, classify each piece, and show you the labeled results. 🎉

> 📍 *Tip:* The example coordinates point to the Bangalore area. Change `BBOX` to any place you like (you can grab coordinates from Google Maps).

---

## 💡 What I learned from this project

- How to **pull real satellite data** from a live API instead of using pre-downloaded files.
- How **ResNet's skip connections** make a real, measurable difference (93% vs 81%).
- How to build a **complete pipeline** — from raw satellite data all the way to final predictions — not just a model in isolation.

---

## 🚀 Ideas for the future

- Use **all the satellite's color bands** (not just red/green/blue) for even better accuracy.
- Save the results as a **real map layer** you can open in QGIS or Google Earth.
- Classify the **entire image** at once to make a full land-cover map.

